_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:136550,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=136550&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/139606&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Setters and \&quot;this\&quot;&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:21,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;10:18&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;Constructors are a special kind of method that gets run automatically when you create an object from a class (or in the lingo, \u0026quot;instantiate\u0026quot; an object).&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:139767,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:136643,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=136643&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/139767&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Constructors&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:22,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;19:46&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;A tutorial on the static keyword in Java. We\u0026#039;ll also take a look at \u0026quot;final\u0026quot;.&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:203660,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:215785,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=215785&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/203660&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Static (and Final)&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:23,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;19:43&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;It\u0026#039;s time to take a closer look at the important topic of formatting and combining strings ....&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:141537,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:138974,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=138974&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/141537&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;String Builder and String Formatting&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:24,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;11:06&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;toString() is a method of the Object class, which is the ultimate parent of all objects in Java. By over-riding it, you can implement a way to create a string representation of your object.&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:145741,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:141115,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=141115&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/145741&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;The toString Method&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:25,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;14:09&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;Inheritance is one of the basic building blocks of OO programs. And yes, believe it or not, it is actually used in the real world -- constantly -- \u0026nbsp;but perhaps most often when working with elaborate external APIs, such as Swing or servlets.&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:146346,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:141950,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=141950&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot