t;16:23&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;It\u0026#039;s finally time to start looking at exceptions .... A major component of the Java language, and one that you\u0026#039;re bound to run across in any sizeable program. Here we\u0026#039;ll look at the two ways of handling exceptions and how they work.&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:196137,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:209903,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=209903&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/196137&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Handling Exceptions&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:38,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;12:11&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;You can throw more than one possible type of exception from a method, and you can catch multiple exceptions in your try-catch block We\u0026#039;ll look at the possibilities here, and also take a look at a common interview/exam question.&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:200573,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:212993,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=212993&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/200573&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Multiple Exceptions&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:39,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;08:49&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;So far we\u0026#039;ve looked at checked exceptions; the kinds of exception that you are forced to handle. But there are also unchecked (runtime) exceptions. These are exceptions that you can handle if you want to, but you\u0026#039;re not forced to. Knowing about the two main kinds of exception is considered an important test of knowledge in Java.&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:212825,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:223252,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=223252&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/212825&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Runtime vs. Checked Exceptions&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:40,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;12:58&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;\u003cdiv class=\&quot;w3c-default\&quot;\u003eAbstract classes allow you to define the parent class of a new hierarchy without having to worry about the user actually instantiating the parent. For instance you could create an \u0026quot;Animal\u0026quot; class just to act as the basis for \u0026quot;Dog\u0026quot;, \u0026quot;Cat, \u0026quot;Sheep\u0026quot; and so on, even defining some functionality in \u0026quot;Animal\u0026quot;, but at the same time preventing the user of your hierarchy from trying to create an \u0026quot;Animal\u0026quot; object (which after all wouldn\u0026#039;t make much sense -- you never encounter an abstract \u0026quot;animal\u0026quot; in the real world; only particular kinds of animals).\u003c/div\u003e&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:214770,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:225335,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=225335&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/214770&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Abstract Classes&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:41,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;17:26&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;To really get serious about reading files in Java, you need to get used to stacking objects inside each other like Russian dolls. Although the code we\u0026#039;ll examine here is complex, in the next tutorial we\u0026#039;ll discover a Java 7 language feature that can simplify it a lot. It\u0026#039;s also a very flexible structure for reading files, since you can read different kinds of files by changing a class or two.&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:229671,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:240527,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=240527&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/229671&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Reading Files With File Reader&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:42,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;11:12&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;The Java 7 Try-With-Resources syntax can massively simplify your file reading/writing code.&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:255769,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:270035,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=270035&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/255769&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Try-With-Resources&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:43,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;06:20&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;A tutorial on writing text files. Which is very similar to reading text files.&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:256668,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:271262,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=271262&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/256668&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Creating and Writing Text Files&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:44,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;17:21&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;\u003cp\u003e \tA tutorial on how to implement the .equals method for your own classes. \u003c/p\u003e&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:1992436,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:2234502,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=2234502&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/1992436&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;The Equals Method&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:45,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;16:33&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;Classes can be declared almost anywhere in Java. In particular, it\u0026#039;s often very useful to declare either static or non-static classes within other classes.\u003cdiv\u003e\u003cspan\u003ehttp://www.caveofprogramming.com/java/inner-classes/\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/div\u003e&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:309536,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:334842,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=334842&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/309536&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Inner Classes&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:46,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;19:20&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;The enum keyword lets you create constants that belong to a fixed set of values (think colours, animals, etc). In the first half of this video we\u0026#039;ll look at basic usage and why we need enum, then we\u0026#039;ll move on to more advanced usage.\u003cdiv\u003e\u003cspan\u003eSource code:\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan\u003ehttp://www.caveofprogramming.com/java/enum/\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/div\u003e&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:313423,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:339465,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=339465&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/313423&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Enum Types: Basic and Advanced Usage&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:47,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;17:26&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;\u003cdiv\u003eRecursion is a programming technique that allows you to solve certain kinds of problems very elegantly. It involves calling a method from itself. Crazy!\u003c/div\u003eSource code: http://www.caveofprogramming.com/java/recursion/&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:320992,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:349072,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=349072&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/320992&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Recursion: A Useful Trick Up Your Sleeve&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:48,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;21:17&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;Serialization is the process of turning objects into a stream of binary data; by serializing objects, you can store them in a file and restore them later from the same file, implementing saving and loading in your application.&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:352723,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:383608,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=383608&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/352723&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Serialization: Saving Objects to Files&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:49,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;14:42&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;\u003cp\u003e\n\tWe can serialize entire arrays (or ArrayLists) just as easily as single objects. I\u0026#039;ll also show you a good trick for serializing multiple objects individually in this tutorial, plus we\u0026#039;ll talk a bit about type erasure.\n\u003c/p\u003e&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:424118,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:464074,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=464074&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/424118&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Serializing Arrays&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:50,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;16:14&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;\u003cp\u003e\n\tTo finish off the stuff about serialization, we\u0026#039;ll take a look at the transient keyword, plus a few things that might catch you out.\n\u003c/p\u003e&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:807408,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:896726,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=896726&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/807408&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;The Transient Keyword and More Serialization&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:51,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;21:30&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;\u003cp\u003e\n\tJava only supports one method of passing values to methods, unlike, e.g. C++. We\u0026#039;ll take a look at exactly how argument passing works in this tutorial (note: source code attached to this lecture; for other lectures, see the source attached to the final lecture).\n\u003c/p\u003e&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:1467250,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:1632880,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=1632880&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/1467250&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Passing by Value&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:52,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;}],&quot;lecture_count&quot;:48,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Programming Core Java&quot;},{&quot;content_length_text&quot;:&quot;03:17:04&quot;,&quot;content_length&quot;:11824,&quot;index&quot;:3,&quot;items&quot;:[{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;09:58&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;The ArrayList class takes the work out of using arrays, by providing you with a resizeable array object.&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:161106,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:152502,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=152502&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/161106&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;ArrayList: Arrays the Easy Way&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:53,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;13:56&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;\u003cp\u003e\n\tIf you want to add items efficiently to somewhere in a list other than the beginning or end, you need a linked list.\n\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\n\tIMPORTANT NOTE: I had misunderstood something when making this video, as pointed out to me by \&quot;kidbabic\&quot; on YouTube among others. If you add or insert something to a LinkedList by specifying an index, the list has to iterate over all items in itself up to that point in order to find the insertion/deletion point. So adding or removing to LinkedList is only faster if you use an iterator, which you have ready pointing at the correct point. See the tutorial on iterators later on for more info.\n\u003c/p\u003e&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:161174,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:152513,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=152513&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/161174&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Linked Lists&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:54,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;09:57&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;Maps let you store key-value pairs, so that for example you can retrieve objects via an ID. HashMap is the most lightweight in terms of memory, and the one you\u0026#039;ll use the most often.&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:161682,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:152911,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=152911&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/161682&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;HashMap: Retrieving Objects via a Key&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:55,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;12:02&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;If you want your map keys to be sorted, you can use special kinds of maps. A lot of what we\u0026#039;ll cover here also applies to sets, which we\u0026#039;ll look at shortly.&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:174232,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:162753,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=162753&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/174232&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Sorted Maps&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:56,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;15:54&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;Used less often than lists or maps, sets are nevertheless great for creating collections of things that are unique --- in other words, for removing duplicates. It\u0026#039;s also very quick to check whether a value exists in a set, whereas checking for something in a list can take a long time in computer terms.&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:174878,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;:null,&quot;video_asset_id&quot;:162816,&quot;preview_url&quot;:&quot;/course/24823/preview/?startPreviewId=162816&quot;,&quot;learn_url&quot;:&quot;/course/java-tutorial/learn/lecture/174878&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Sets&quot;,&quot;object_index&quot;:57,&quot;item_type&quot;:&quot;lecture&quot;},{&quot;can_be_previewed&quot;:false,&quot;content_summary&quot;:&quot;11:20&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;\u003cdiv class=\&quot;w3c-default\&quot;\u003eIf you want to use objects of your own classes in sets, or you want to use them as the keys in maps, you need to do a couple of little things ....\u003c/div\u003e&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:176191,&quot;icon_class&quot;:&quot;udi udi-play-circle&quot;,&quot;is_coding_exercise&quot;:false,&quot;landing_page_url&quot;